10. Usage of Cursors


Usage of Cursors
1. Aim

To create and use a cursor to retrieve and display records row by row from a table.

2. Theory

A cursor is a pointer used in PL/SQL to process multiple rows one by one from a query result.

Steps to use a cursor:

Declare cursor
Open cursor
Fetch records
Close cursor
3. Program / Procedure
Step 1: Create Table
CREATE TABLE Student (
    RollNo INT PRIMARY KEY,
    Name VARCHAR(30),
    Dept VARCHAR(10)
);
Step 2: Insert Data
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (101, 'Ravi', 'CSE');
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (102, 'Anu', 'ECE');
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (103, 'Kiran', 'EEE');
4. Cursor Program
SET SERVEROUTPUT ON;

DECLARE
    CURSOR c1 IS SELECT Name, Dept FROM Student;
    v_name Student.Name%TYPE;
    v_dept Student.Dept%TYPE;
BEGIN
    OPEN c1;

    LOOP
        FETCH c1 INTO v_name, v_dept;
        EXIT WHEN c1%NOTFOUND;

        DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Name: ' || v_name || ' Dept: ' || v_dept);
    END LOOP;

    CLOSE c1;
END;
5. Output (What to Write)
Name: Ravi Dept: CSE
Name: Anu Dept: ECE
Name: Kiran Dept: EEE
6. Result

Cursor is successfully used to fetch and display records row by row.
